🤘 Hey folks,

Today is the one year anniversary of my latest album #StandArt and I am very excited to present to you a short film by my sister Melanya Hamasyan. The film feature an arrangement of a song from the album called I Should Care (A. Stordhal) featuring @ambroseire. Here is a message from the director about the process of how this film came together. 

#TigranHamasyan #IShouldCare #NightOdyssey 

🔥 Enjoy the full film via the link in bio!

"In autumn of 2021,  my brother proposed an idea to shoot a short film(as an alternative to a music video) inspired by a song from his most recent- still unnamed at the time -album.  Of course I was immediately excited by the idea,  and even more so when I discovered that the piece he was suggesting was I Should Care,  a composition which I had initially discovered and loved by the interpretation of the great Thelonious Monk.  Another prospect for the project also interested me - that is, shooting the film in Armenia, which was something I had wanted to do.

Hearing Tigran’s arrangement accompanied by the wonderful Ambrose Akinmusire (a collaboration I had had the pleasure to witness a few years back) provoked a complexity of images and emotions which inspired the idea for the film.  There was a contemporaneity I could hear in the interpretation - a postmodern breath which was all too relevant in the context of an Armenian winter, when the grey of the everyday seemed to be longer, deeper and lonelier. 

In the outskirts of the capital, where I lived, was a landscape which was visually disorientating, a hybrid of the urban, industrial, and residential - chaos in disharmony reflecting our post-modern existence. Yet still within winter’s solitude, were visible the illuminated scenes of human presence.  The film, Night Odyssey became a search for meaning and the awakening from a perpetually disorienting chaos of our contemporary landscape".

✨ Hey folks! Lately @armpublictv reminded me of one of my first interviews with @gohargasparyan. Enjoy the deep talk!

🇦🇲 It's incredibly challenging to make statements and comments under the current situation, where more than 120,000 people, including 30,000 children, who are ethnic Armenians of Artsakh/Nagorno Karabakh, have been strategically cut off and blockaded by Azerbaijan's unlawful military for 9 months now. Since the September 19-20 aggression, it has been total chaos for these people, with records of civilians being killed... They couldn't even be displaced. I guess ethnic cleansing is still a concern in Azerbaijan, and global entities and human rights advocates seem to be turning a blind eye. Family members can't find each other, many are missing, stuck in limbo, and confined to their basements with no access to food and hygienic products, all while being hunted and surveilled by the Azeri military.

I simply wish for these people who have suffered enough to reach safety as soon as possible through a secure route, at the very least, while we figure out how to help. Innocent civilians deserve and have the right to live.

naïve is pleased to announce a new signature with the famous composer, pianist and keyboardist @tigranhamasyan 🖤

The already renowned virtuoso distinguishes himself by offering a musicality at the crossroads of jazz, folklore and rock, whose intensity draws its source especially from the artist's Armenian heritage.

About this new partnership with naïve, Tigran Hamasyan said: “I am super excited to join naïve Records and Believe for my upcoming project.” 

@johann_audiffren, A&R & Marketing Manager at naïve, said: ”I am more than proud to welcome Tigran Hamasyan at naïve. He's been a personal inspiration for many years, and I look forward to sharing this amazing upcoming project. Thanks to @pascal_pilorget and the team at @gsteps for their support.” 

📷 ©️Davide Monteleone

“Night Odyssey” - a short film by Melanya Hamasyan where you will find an arrangement I made of an incredible beautiful song “I Should Care” by Alex Stordhal featuring the great Ambrose Akinmusire on trumpet. 

Melanya Hamasyan writes: 

“In autumn of 2021, my brother proposed an idea to shoot a short film (as an alternative to a music video) inspired by a song from his most recent—still unnamed at the time—album. Of course I was immediately excited by the idea,  and even more so when I discovered that the piece he was suggesting was ‘I Should Care,’ a composition which I had initially discovered and loved by the interpretation of the great Thelonious Monk. Another prospect for the project also interested me - that is, shooting the film in Armenia, which was something I had wanted to do.

“Hearing Tigran’s arrangement accompanied by the wonderful Ambrose Akinmusire (a collaboration I had had the pleasure to witness a few years back) provoked a complexity of images and emotions which inspired the idea for the film. There was a contemporaneity I could hear in the interpretation—a postmodern breath which was all too relevant in the context of an Armenian winter, when the grey of the everyday seemed to be longer, deeper and lonelier. 

“In the outskirts of the capital, where I lived, was a landscape which was visually disorientating, a hybrid of the urban, industrial, and residential—chaos in disharmony reflecting our post-modern existence. Yet still within winter’s solitude, were visible the illuminated scenes of human presence.  The film, ‘Night Odyssey,’ became a search for meaning and the awakening from a perpetually disorienting chaos of our contemporary landscape.”

🔥Chicago!  March 17th! The Call Within at the Lincoln Hall. Cancel your s...t and be there!

🎧 Hey Folks! The great @ecm_records label has created an inspiring playlist of the music of Komitas and G.I. Gurdjieff that has been coming out on the label throughout many years. Check it out!

--------------------------------

ECM Records text:

"Georges I. Gurdjieff and Komitas Vardapet, near contemporaries with strong roots in Armenia, were polymaths with parallel interests in sacred and secular music of multiple traditions.  Komitas, often heralded as the father of modern music in Armenia, was a priest and a composer as well as an ethnomusicologist who transcribed thousands of regional tunes.  Gurdjieff was a maverick esoteric teacher whose compositions were reflections of his travels and the chants, hymns and dances heard en route.  Musicians at ECM have enjoyed exploring the works of both men, as this fascinating playlist reveals (link in bio!)

Among them @keithjarrettsolo ,  Levon Eskenian's @gurdjieffensemble , @tigran.hamasyan , Kim Kashkashian, Tigran Mansurian , Anja Lechner @cellanja , Jan Garbarek, Norma Winstone and more."
a music journey of self-discovery
